The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, April 08, 2004 				 Bharti bonds with $100 m
																								New Delhi, April 7 (PTI): Sunil Mittal-promoted Bharti group today announced successful completion of $100 million foreign convertible currency bond (FCCB) issue and also decided to retain 15 per cent of the oversubscription.																								The issue received an overwhelming response from the foreign investors and generated a demand exceeding $1 billion worth within two hours of the launch, a Bharti spokesperson said.																								The conversion price under the bond works out to be Rs 232 reflecting about 40 per cent premium on todays closing price of Bharti Tele-Ventures at Rs 166.																								The five-year bond carries zero coupon rate with yield to maturity at 2.25 per cent by way of redemption premium, the spokesperson said adding ABN Amro and Deutsche Bank acted as joint book runners to the transaction.																								Akhil Gupta, joint managing director of Bharti, said, The resounding success of the FCCB issue reflects the strength of the company and investors confidence. 																								The proceeds of the bond issue would be utilised for meeting the capital expenditure planned by the company during the year.																								Bharti operates in fixed, GSM-based mobile, national and international long-distance telephony.																								The company had recently acquired new unified licences for six new circles and envisaged an investment of over Rs 700 crore to roll out the infrastructure for offering cellular mobile services.																								Besides this, the company has been aggressively eyeing acquisitions in the telecom sector. 
